In 1967, one hairy-legged vampire bat (
Diphylla ecaudata
) was documented in an aban-
doned tunnel near Comstock, Texas [62,63]. This record is approximately 700 km north of
the next most northerly record of this species [63], and may represent an anomalous record a
long distance from regularly occupied habitat [64] or may represent an as yet unidentified
population in the Me
xico-Texas borderlands [62]. Nevertheless, this record indicates that bats
in the subfamily

that the vampire bat populations in north-eastern Me
xico are expanding spatially and demo-
graphically [38], that vampire bats have been recently documented within 50 km of the Texas
border, and that there is a contiguous corridor of potentially-suitable habitat between north-
eastern Me
xico and southern Texas [47], it would not be unreasonable to hypothesize that the
southern tip of Texas could become occupied by vampire bats in the future.

Cuba or by airline and marine transportation channels that connect currently occupied vam-
pire bat habitat with southern Florida. Vampire bats do not currently occur on Cuba, but our
